ads.author: Dulce Maria
ads.title: Bulova Lunar Pilot 96B251. Ozark, AL. If this appears posted, it is available.
ads.description: The Bulova Lunar Pilot 96B251 is a special edition chronograph that commemorates the Apollo 15 mission, where an original Bulova watch was worn on the Moon's surface. The watch is known for its blend of historical significance and modern engineering, featuring an ultra-accurate high-performance quartz movement. Key Features and Specifications Movement: Powered by Bulova's proprietary high-performance quartz (HPQ) movement (caliber NP20), which vibrates at a frequency of 262 kHz, offering unparalleled accuracy of just a few seconds per year. Case: A 45mm diameter, 316L surgical-grade stainless steel case with a sandblasted, silver-tone finish. A newer, smaller 43.5mm version is also available, but the 96B251 reference is the original 45mm size. Dial and Crystal: Features a black, multi-layered dial with luminous hands and markers, protected by an anti-reflective sapphire crystal for superior scratch resistance and clarity. It includes three chronograph subdials and a date window at the 4:30 position. Straps: The watch comes as a box set with two interchangeable straps: one textured black leather strap and one black nylon NATO strap featuring a leather patch that commemorates the mission date: "08021971". A strap change tool is included in the presentation box. Water Resistance: Rated for 50 meters (5 ATM), suitable for still water swimming but not high-impact water sports. Design and History The 96B251 is a modern re-issue of the personal chronograph worn by astronaut Dave Scott during the Apollo 15 mission after his NASA-issued Omega Speedmaster malfunctioned. The modern version maintains the distinctive vintage design of the original, with some upgrades like the durable sapphire crystal and the enhanced quartz movement. Reviewers often praise its aesthetic appeal, excellent readability, and unique space-exploration history, sometimes noting its larger size as a potential consideration for smaller wrists.

ads.title: Lethal enforcers 2 arcade cabinet
ads.description: This is for a lethal enforcers part 2, gunfighters arcade machine. It works, pretty much fine. The monitor has some issues. It needs to be recapped. But it plays just fine. The player two gun I can't get to connect. But I think it's because it's missing the optical lens on it. Not sure how it came out. But it was missing, when I got the machine. The game will let you play all the way through, just fine. But the screen has what they call monitor fog appearing on one side. The coin mechs work fine. Everything is all there. It has a brand new power supply, put in it.

ads.author: Nicole Aston
ads.title: Area 51 Atari Arcade Machine
ads.description: Must pick up today (SATURDAY 12/20) in Jax Beach off Beach & 3rd Street. From the manufacturer: The 1995 video game Area 51 is a light gun shooter arcade game developed by Messa Logic and published by Atari Games. Players take on a role of a member of the Strategic Tactical Advanced Alien Response (S.T.A.A.R.) team, fighting against an alien invasion by the Akron and their zombie-like creations at the infamous Area 51 military base. The game was known for its use of digitalized video and sprites, and it was later ported to home consoles like the PlayStation, Sega Saturn and Windows. The machine does need SOME work. I’m not sure why though. It turns on, the screen is no longer visible, you used to be able to play it for a while, it has sound. Always wanted this machine and sad to see it go. Moved into an apartment and don’t have the room for it.
